\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The equations in Section~\ref{sec:theory} and 
the case study in Section~\ref{sec:case_studies}
enable the following observations.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Economy-wide energy backfire is observed}
\label{sec:backfire_observed}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Installation of LED bulbs is likely to cause economy-wide energy backfire 
when economy-wide rebound is considered, 
because Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW_val} shows $Re_{EW} > 1$.
**** Discuss how this result agrees (or doesn't) with other economy-wide backfire estimates
from the literature. ****


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Conditions for economy-wide backfire}
\label{sec:conditinos_for_backfire}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Economy-wide backfire occurs when $Re_{EW} > 1$, or, with reference to Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW},
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:backfire_inequality_1}
  1 - (1 - k I_{E_f} P) (1 - Re_{dev}) > 1 \; .
\end{equation}
%
Simplification gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:backfire_inequality_2}
  (1 - k I_{E_f} P) (1 - Re_{dev}) < 0 \; .
\end{equation}

It is expected that $Re_{dev} < 1$ and
$(1 - Re_{dev}) > 0$. 
If it were not so, 
energy efficiency interventions would be uneconomic for the efficiency device owner.
Thus, the inequality of Eq.~\ref{eq:backfire_inequality_2} simplifies to
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:backfire_inequality_3}
  1 - k I_{E_f} P < 0 \; .
\end{equation}
%
Solving for $P$ gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:backfire_inequality_4}
  P > \frac{1}{k I_{E_f}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Substituting for $P$ from Eq.~\ref{eq:P_eqn} gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:backfire_inequality}
  p_{E_f} - \frac{C_{install}}{(1 - Re_{dev}) E_{sav,dev,expected}} > \frac{1}{k I_{E_f}} \; .
\end{equation}

Inspection of Eqs.~\ref{eq:backfire_inequality_4} and~\ref{eq:backfire_inequality} reveals that
economy-wide backfire is more likely to occur when
%
\begin{itemize}
	
	\item $P$ is large (it is economically advantageous for the energy efficiency device owner 
	      to install energy-efficient devices), which occurs when
	%
  \begin{itemize}

    \item $p_{E_f}$ is large 
          (energy is expensive),

    \item $Re_{dev}$ is small (rebound at the device-level is negligible), and
    
    \item $\frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev,expected}}$ is small 
          (implementing energy efficiency is inexpensive relative to the expected energy savings);

  \end{itemize}
%
  \item $k$ is large, because $\mpc \rightarrow 1$ 
        (the multiplier effect is large, because nearly all freed cash is respent); and
  
  \item $I_{E_f}$ is large 
        (the economy is very energy intensive).
        
\end{itemize}


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{How to avoid backfire}
\label{sec:avoiding_backfire}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

When the purpose of energy efficiency is to \emph{reduce} energy consumption,
economy-wide backfire is undesirable.
Given the above results, 
this section uses the case study to explore
the sensitivity of economy-wide rebound to the various parameters in Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW}
and ways to avoid backfire.
In particular, the effects of 
the price of final energy~($p_{E_f}$), 
device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$), 
the expected unit cost of an energy efficiency intervention~$\left(\frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev,expected}}\right)$,
the marginal propensity to consume~($\mpc$), and 
final energy intensity~($R_{E_p}$)
are each considered in turn.


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Effect of $p_{E_f}$} 
\label{sec:effect_p_E_f}
%------------------------------

<<Re_EWvsp_graph, echo = FALSE, fig.align = "center", fig.height = 2.5, fig.width = 4, fig.cap = "Variation of economy-wide rebound with the price of final energy. For this graph, $I_{E_f}$, $\\mpc$, $\\frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev,expected}}$, and $Re_{dev}$ are constant at their values shown in Section~\\ref{sec:case_studies}. The red point indicates nominal values of $Re_{EW}$ and $p_{E_f}$  from the case study.">>=
p_E_f_for_Re_EW1_light <- 1 / (k * I_E_f) + C_install_light / ((1 - Re_dev_light) * E_sav_dev_expected_light)
data.frame(p_E_f = seq(from = 0.5*p_E_f_light, to = 1.2*p_E_f_light, by = 0.01*p_E_f_light)) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(
    Re_EW = Re_EW_func(MPC = mpc, I_E_f = I_E_f, p_E_f = p_E_f, 
                       C_install = C_install_light, 
                       E_sav_dev_expected = E_sav_dev_expected_light, 
                       Re_dev = Re_dev_light) 
  ) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = p_E_f, y = Re_EW)) + 
  # Guide lines for nominal values
  geom_vline(xintercept = p_E_f_light, colour = "gray", size = 0.1) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = Re_EW_light, colour = "gray", size = 0.1) +
  # Guide lines for Re_EW = 1
  geom_vline(xintercept = p_E_f_for_Re_EW1_light, colour = "gray", size = 0.1) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1, colour = "gray", size = 0.1) +
  # Add the line
  geom_line() + 
  # Add the point
  geom_point(x = p_E_f_light, y = Re_EW_light, colour = "red", size = 3) + 
  # Add the correct labels.
  labs(x = expression(p[E[f]]*" [$/kW-hr]"), y = expression(Re[EW]*" [-]")) + 
  MKHthemes::xy_theme()
@

Fig.~\ref{fig:Re_EWvsp_graph} shows the variation of economy-wide rebound~($Re_{EW}$)
with the price of final energy~$p_{E_f}$.
As discussed above, economy-wide backfire can be avoided 
when when the price of final energy is low.
To find the value of the price of final energy at which 
economy-wide rebound is 1 (the boundary between rebound and backfire),
Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW} can be solved for $p_{E_f}$
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:p_E_f_for_Re_EW_1}
  p_{E_f} = \frac{1}{k I_{E_f}} \left( 1 - \frac{1 - Re_{DW}}{1 - Re_{dev}} \right) + \frac{C_{install}}{(1 - Re_{dev}) E_{sav,dev,expected}}    \; ,
\end{equation}
%
and $Re_{EW}$ set to 1.
Doing so yields
$p_{E_f} = \Sexpr{format(p_E_f_for_Re_EW1_light, digits = 3)}$~\$/kW-hr
for the case study in Section~\ref{sec:case_studies}, 
a \Sexpr{format((p_E_f_light - p_E_f_for_Re_EW1_light)/p_E_f_light * 100, digits = 3)}~\% reduction
compared to the baseline price of final energy~(\Sexpr{format(p_E_f_light, digits = 3)} \$/kW-hr).


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Effect of $Re_{dev}$} 
\label{sec:effect_Re_dev}
%------------------------------

<<Re_EWvsRedev_graph, echo = FALSE, fig.align = "center", fig.height = 2.5, fig.width = 4, fig.cap = "Variation of economy-wide rebound with device-level rebound. For this graph, $k$, $I_{E_f}$, $p_{E_f}$, $C_{install}$, and $E_{sav,dev,expected}$ are constant at their values shown in Section~\\ref{sec:case_studies}. The red point indicates nominal values of $Re_{EW}$ and $Re_{dev}$ from the case study.">>=
# Calculate the Re_dev value at which Re_EW = 1
Re_dev_for_Re_EW1_light <- (1 - k*I_E_f*(p_E_f_light - C_install_light/E_sav_dev_expected_light)) / (1 - k*I_E_f*p_E_f_light)
data.frame(Re_dev = seq(from = 0, to = 1.4, by = 0.051)) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(
    Re_EW = Re_EW_func(MPC = mpc, I_E_f = I_E_f, p_E_f = p_E_f_light, 
                       C_install = C_install_light, 
                       E_sav_dev_expected = E_sav_dev_expected_light, 
                       Re_dev = Re_dev)
  ) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Re_dev, y = Re_EW)) + 
  # Guide lines that cross at nominal values
  geom_hline(yintercept = Re_EW_light, colour = "gray", size = 0.1) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = Re_dev_light, colour = "gray", size = 0.1) +
  # Guide lines for Re_EW = 1
  geom_vline(xintercept = Re_dev_for_Re_EW1_light, colour = "gray", size = 0.1) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1, colour = "gray", size = 0.1) +
  # The line itself.
  geom_line() + 
  # The red dot for nominal values
  geom_point(x = Re_dev_light, y = Re_EW_light, colour = "red", size = 3) + 
  labs(x = expression(Re[dev]*" [-]"), y = expression(Re[EW]*" [-]")) + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(from = 0, to = 1.4, by = 0.2)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(from = 0.4, to = 2, by = 0.2)) +
  MKHthemes::xy_theme()
@

The variation of economy-wide rebound with device-level rebound is shown
in Fig.~\ref{fig:Re_EWvsRedev_graph}.
The slope of the line is negative, 
as shown by Eq.~\ref{eq:dRe_EW/dRe_dev_val},
indicating that decreasing device-level rebound 
leads to increasing economy-wide rebound, even backfire.
Although this result may be counterintuitive initially,
it is perfectly reasonable.
When $Re_{dev}$ decreases, the owner of the energy efficiency device has more 
freed cash to re-spend in the economy.
With more freed cash re-spent in the economy, 
the multiplier effect is more pronounced, 
and new demand for final energy (at the final energy intensity of the economy)
grows.
The converse is also true.
When $Re_{dev}$ increases, the owner of the energy efficiency device has less 
freed cash to spend in the economy.
With less freed cash spent in the economy, 
the multiplier effect is muted, 
and new demand for final energy (at the final energy intensity of the economy)
diminishes.

When device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$) is large enough,
economy-wide backfire can be avoided ($Re_{EW} < 1$).
To find the value of device-level rebound at which 
economy-wide rebound is 1 (the boundary between rebound and backfire),
Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW} can be solved for $Re_{dev}$
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:Re_dev_for_Re_EW_1}
  Re_{dev} = \frac{Re_{EW} - k I_{E_f} \left(p_{E_f} - \frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev,expected}} \right)}{1 - k I_{E_f} p_{E_f}} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
and $Re_{EW}$ set to 1.
Doing so yields 
$Re_{dev} = \Sexpr{format(Re_dev_for_Re_EW1_light, digits = 2)}$ to achieve $Re_{EW} = 1$
for the case study in Section~\ref{sec:case_studies}.
So economy-wide backfire is avoided only when device-level rebound 
takes back nearly all~($\Sexpr{format(Re_dev_for_Re_EW1_light * 100, digits = 2)}$~\%) 
of the monetary savings the owner of the energy efficiency device would have expected. 
To avoid backfire, 
the energy efficiency device must be only marginally economic for the device owner.


